        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Pottsville</placeName>
                <date>October 13<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1851</date>.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)"><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>,</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Your very excellent letter in<lb/> answer to my note of inquiry of
                last <date>Monday</date>, was received in<lb/> the latter part of the week. And I am
                unable sufficiently to<lb/> thank you for your kindness and promptness in
                furnishing<lb/> me an answer. On the subject referred to, it is all that I<lb/>
                could desire, and has satisfied my mind on a point which gave<lb/> me some
                perplexity, and in regard to which I was unable to obtain<lb/> any satisfactory
                information. Nothing would give me greater<lb/> pleasure than a personal
                acquaintance with you, and the priv-<lb/>-iledge of hearing you converse on matters
                which have always<lb/> been deeply interesting to me, and which are common to
                both<lb/> systems of religion, to which we respectfully adhere.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I am thankful, also, for the information you give with<lb/>
                reference to the works mentioned in your letter. I will be<lb/> pleased to purchase
                them. And as I will be in the city about<lb/> the first of <date>November</date>, I
                will embrace the opportunity you<lb/> kindly offer, and will call on you in order to
                obtain them.<lb/> From what you say of them, it appears that they are just<lb/> the
                books I want. In order that you may know<lb/> something about me, (not for the
                purpose of laying any claim<lb/> to a title,) I will state that I am a minster of
                the Asso-<lb/>ciate Reformed Presbyterian Church—the same denomina-</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>tion with which <persName>Rev. I. B. Dales</persName> of
                    <placeName>Philad.</placeName> is connected;<lb/> with whom, perhaps, you are
                acquainted.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The misnomer by which I addressed you in the direc-<lb/>tion of my
                letter, you will please attribute to my ignorance<lb/> of your present position. I
                knew that you were once the<lb/> “minister of the <placeName>Cherry St.</placeName>
                Synagogue.” and had the pleasure<lb/> of being present once, when you officiated:
                but I was not<lb/> aware that <add>your connection with that</add> congregation had
                been dissolved, at least in a<lb/> ministerial capacity. Such difficulties will
                happen to the<lb/> best of men. Said I have generally discovered that
                congrega-<lb/>tions acting in that manner, eventually find to their own<lb/>
                chagrin, that in maltreating their minister, they have been<lb/> “kicking against
                the pricks”—hurting themselves more than<lb/> him. I will be glad to have a letter
                from you again,<lb/> and at any time you may find it convenient to write</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">With great regard</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Yours &amp;c,</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <hi rend="underline">
                    <persName role="author">D. J. Caruahan</persName>
                </hi>
            </p>
